Psychological Effects of Racial Bias in Maternal Healthcare

AP Seminar

Fall 2023

Introduction to the Issue

.

While looking at potential research topics under the broader theme of bias in healthcare, I began taking an interest in the psychological side of racial discrimination or bias. When researching the psychology behind recieving bias I discovered postpartum depression (PPD), which is an extreme depressive state that affects women after giving birth. PPD is a very serious issue, with negative effects for both the mother and child, as the 'motherly bond' is damaged or broken, which causes unwillingness to breastfeed or care for the baby. Moreover, I was able to find research proving a link between receiving bias and showing PPD symptoms, highlighting another facet of how destructive bias can be.

Bias in Healthcare Settings

They treat you different, even with the way they greet you. —... because you African-American. Participant, Okoro et al. 2020

Researchers Olihe Okoro and colleagues collected testimony from several Black women who felt they had recieved bias in recent hospital or doctor visits. One common theme, as illustrated above, was the idea of implicit bias, which is where bias shows subtly through actions rather than outright. Furthermore, several participants also noted that their healthcare providers seemed to jump to conclusions oddly quickly, with one woman reporting she was denied medication, with the doctor reportedly acting as if she thought the woman was an addict. Lewis et al. concurs, with similar evidence showing implicit bias, and stating that such bias can cause mistrust in the healthcare system and reluctance to seek help. Aside from the trust issues, this also means that illnesses and health complications can go untreated and potentially worsen, creating increased physical harm on top of mental harm.

Psychological Effects

According to professor of psychology Mark Manning, self-presentation concerns can prevent African American patients from disclosing health information, especially if they expect unfair treatment. A distrust in providers can lead to poorer communication, and as a result, worsened adherence to treatmemt plans and and increase in hesitance to return. Additionally, a New Jersey study shows that 4.6 times the number of Black mothers surveyed reported feeling biased against, and mothers who reported bias were 4.4 times more likely to experience PPD symptoms.

Promising Solution

A study by Shannon McMorrow has shown that community-based mental health promotion can help to lessen the effects of bias, and can provide skills for managing stress and anxiety which can help combat PPD. In the study, 93 participants (92% were Black) completed pre, post, and 8-week follow up surveys on their mental health, with a large positive increase between the pre and post assessments, with a minor dropoff at 8 weeks. Moreover, participants showed an increase in behavioral tactics for managing stress like mindful breathing, with qualitative data showing that participants generally demonstrated use of program concepts. So, this sounds like a great way to help, but is it actually in use anywhere? Yes!
The California Black Women's Health Project is a group based in California that holds meetingws for women of color that follow many aspects of McMorrow's findings. The group focuses on what they call "Sister Circles" where small, tight-knit groups of people discuss with eachother. Additionally, a pilot program in Indiana that is similar to teh CABWHP asked participants how they felt, with one stating that,
“Well I think, that being African American-led, being with sisters, with the women that have gone through what I have gone through - I see me when I see them and I can relate. Participant, Nicolaidis et al. 2013

To Conclude

Given the reported prevalence of bias in healthcare and its effects on mothers who experience it, something needs to be done. With solid data and testimony that smaller community mental health groups are helpful in mitigating depression and anxiety, they are a promising solution that is actually already implemented with groups like the CABWHP.

Thank you
